Text Mining

January 6, 2018

Goals

The tasks to be accomplished in this milestone (towards developing a NLP - natural language processing - application) report are:

Exploratory analysis - perform a thorough exploratory analysis of the data, understanding the distribution of words and relationship between the words in the corpora.

Understand frequencies of words and word pairs - build figures and tables to understand variation in the frequencies of words and word pairs in the data.

Read Files

First we read the three text sources, blog, news, and twitter, and create a list of the three documents.

blog <- readLines("en_US.blogs.txt", skipNul = TRUE)
news <- readLines("en_US.news.txt", skipNul = TRUE)
twitter <- readLines("en_US.twitter.txt", skipNul = TRUE)


# Text sources are put into a list and traversed to calculate length and word count

wordCountFunc <- function(myList){sum(str_count(myList, "\\S+"))}

 #Data frame to store counts
 df <- data.frame(textSource=c("blog", "news", "twitter"),lineCount=NA, wordCount = NA)


 # Put corpora into a list
 myList <- list(blog=blog, news=news, twitter=twitter)

 # Get line count and word count for each corpus
 df$lineCount <- sapply(myList, length)
 df$wordCount <- sapply(myList, wordCountFunc)

Exploratory analysis of a training data set

Next, we create a sample list, consisting of about 5% of the original list consisting of all the blog, news, and twitter documents, using the rbinom function.

# Create a data frame for samples
sampleDF <- data.frame(textSource=c("blog", "news", "tewitter"), lineCount=NA, wordCount=NA)

# Create a list of random variables
set.seed(135)
percent <- 0.05
randoms <- lapply(myList, function(x) rbinom(x, 1, percent))

# Create a new, empty list to store random selections
sampList <- list(blog=NA, news=NA, twitter=NA)

# Traverse each element of the orginal list, selecting ~x% of the sample, as determined by rbinom
for (i in 1:length(myList)) {
        sampList[[i]] <- myList[[i]][randoms[[i]]==1]        
}


# Get counts of sample list
sampleDF$lineCount <- sapply(sampList, length)
sampleDF$wordCount <- sapply(sampList, wordCountFunc)

Preparing Corpora for word analysis

We create a corpora using our sample list and the corpora will be cleaned up by removing stop-words, curse words, removeing hashtags and twitter handles from the twitter texts and by removing other unicode characters.

# Helper functions 
removeURL <- function(x) gsub("http:[[:alnum:]]*|https:[[:alnum:]]*", "", x)
removeHashTags <- function(x) gsub("#\\S+", "", x)
removeTwitterHandles <- function(x) gsub("@\\S+|[^[:alnum:] ]", "", x)
removeOther <- function(x) gsub("^\\w+[<].+[>][<].+[>]|[<].+[>]([<].+[>])?|[^[:ascii:]]", "", x, perl=T)

# Create corpus class
textCorpus <- VCorpus(VectorSource(sampList))
#inspect(VCorpus(textCorpus))



# Remove twitter handles and hashtags
textCorpus["twitter"] <- tm_map(textCorpus["twitter"], content_transformer(removeHashTags))
textCorpus["twitter"] <- tm_map(textCorpus["twitter"], content_transformer(removeTwitterHandles))
textCorpus["news"] <- tm_map(textCorpus["news"], content_transformer(removeOther))

# Other transformations
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, content_transformer(removeURL))
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, content_transformer(tolower))
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removeNumbers)

# Remove curse words - curse words file loaded locally
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removeWords, curseWords)
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, removePunctuation)
textCorpus <- tm_map(textCorpus, content_transformer(removeOther))

Next, the Corpora are put into their own Term Document Matrix and ready for further analysis. Words smaller than three characters are omitted.

# Single tokenizers
twitterTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["twitter"], control=list(wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))
newsTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["news"], control=list(wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))

blogTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["blog"], control=list(wordLengths = c(3, Inf)))

Word analysis

The corpora are now ready to be explored for distinct word counts and most frequent words.

# Put word count from term-document matrices into data frames
freqBlog <- data.frame(word=blogTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = blogTdm$v)

freqNews <- data.frame(word=newsTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = newsTdm$v)

freqTwitter <- data.frame(word=twitterTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = twitterTdm$v)

Coming attractions - ngrams and prediction algorithms

BigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 2))
TrigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 3, max = 3))
FourgramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 4, max = 4))


trigramBlogTdm <- TermDocumentMatrix(textCorpus["blog"], control = list(tokenize = TrigramTokenizer))

freqTrigramBlog <- data.frame(word = trigramBlogTdm$dimnames$Terms, frequency = trigramBlogTdm$v)


freqTrigramBlog <- arrange(freqTrigramBlog, -frequency)
